=========================================================
std::thread::join() - Interview Notes
=========================================================

What is join()?
---------------------------------------------------------

join() waits for the associated thread to finish execution.

The calling thread (usually the main thread) blocks until the worker thread completes.

Syntax
---------------------------------------------------------

t.join();

Example
---------------------------------------------------------

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>

using namespace std;

void worker()
{
    cout << "Worker Thread\n";
}

int main()
{
    thread t(worker);

    t.join();

    cout << "Main Thread Finished\n";
}

Output
---------------------------------------------------------

Worker Thread
Main Thread Finished

=========================================================
Why do we use join()?
=========================================================

• Waits for the worker thread to finish.
• Ensures the thread completes before the program exits.
• Prevents std::terminate() from being called.
• Synchronizes the main thread with the worker thread.

=========================================================
joinable()
=========================================================

joinable() checks whether a std::thread object is associated
with an active thread of execution.

Syntax

t.joinable();

Returns

true  -> Thread can be joined or detached.
false -> Thread is not associated with any thread.

Example

thread t(worker);

if (t.joinable())
{
    t.join();
}

After join()

t.joinable()   // false

After detach()

t.joinable()   // false

Default constructed thread

thread t;

t.joinable()   // false

=========================================================
What happens if join() is not called?
=========================================================

If a std::thread object is destroyed while it is still joinable,
its destructor calls:

std::terminate()

and the program terminates abnormally.

Example

thread t(worker);

// No join()
// No detach()

// Program ends -> std::terminate()

=========================================================
What happens internally?
=========================================================

Main Thread                 Worker Thread
---------------------------------------------------------
Create thread  ----------->  Starts executing

Calls join()
Blocks and waits  <--------  Finishes execution

Main thread resumes

=========================================================
Important Points
=========================================================

✔ join() can be called only once.
✔ After join(), the thread is no longer joinable.
✔ After detach(), the thread is no longer joinable.
✔ Always check joinable() before calling join().
✔ Calling join() on a non-joinable thread throws std::system_error.
✔ join() blocks the calling thread.

=========================================================
Interview Questions
=========================================================

Q. What is join()?

join() blocks the calling thread until the associated worker thread finishes execution.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What is joinable()?

joinable() checks whether a std::thread object owns an active thread that can be joined or detached.*****

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why do we use joinable()?

To avoid calling join() or detach() on a non-joinable thread, which would throw a std::system_error.*********

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why do we use join()?

To wait for a thread to finish and ensure it completes before the std::thread object is destroyed.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What happens if we don't call join() or detach()?

The destructor of a joinable std::thread calls std::terminate(), causing abnormal program termination.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Does join() kill the thread?

No.

The worker thread runs until it finishes naturally.
join() simply waits for it to complete.

